[Like `typeof(T?)`](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/76603), `default(T?)` only has a meaning distinct from `default(T)` when `T` has a struct constraint. And when it _does_ have a distinct meaning, you never really need to write `default(T?)`. It's clearer as `null`.

However, unlike `typeof(T?)` which is in the same boat (modulo https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/76603), `default(T?)` is allowed without an error or even a hint that you're doing something that appears different from `default(T)`, but is not. ([SharpLab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:CYLg1APgAgTABAYQLACgDeq5blALHAWQB4AVAPgAoBKTbDFbRuANwEMAnOVuAXjmACmAM1YBXADYAXCiSoBuWkxYc4AI179hYqTID88xXAC+qI0A))

```cs
class C
{
    void M<T>()
    {
        _ = default(T);
        _ = default(T?); // No warning, though this just means default(T)
    }
}
```

To make matters worse, imagine if `default(T?)` was used for something, yielding a default struct value.

```cs
class C
{
    void M<T>(T p)
    {
        T? zero = default(T?);

        if (Equals(p, zero))
        {
        }
    }
}
```

When you call `M<int>`, it will obtain `zero` as `0` via `default(T?)`.

But then you decide to add a struct constraint. The code silently changes meaning, and `zero` is obtained as `null` via `default(T?)`. Through constraining `T` to a subset of the domain that was correctly working before, the code silently stops working properly _in the struct T_ domain.

`typeof(T?)` is disallowed when there is a class constraint. This makes sense, because it could mean nothing different from `typeof(T)` anyway. Especially since the _struct_ constraint gives `typeof(T?)` a very distinct meaning, it seems wise to block the syntax `typeof(T?)` when it does not have that distinct `Nullable<T>` meaning.

```cs
class C
{
    void M<T>() where T : class
    {
        // ❌ CS8639 The typeof operator cannot be used on a nullable reference type
        _ = typeof(T?);
    }
}
```

However, when C# 9 made it possible to say `T?` inside a method without a struct or class constraint, meaning "defaultable," this exact same situation became possible again, and this time it was not disallowed:

```cs
class C
{
    void M<T>()
    {
        // No error, but this is in the same boat.
        _ = typeof(T?);
    }
}
```

The original rationale that applied when blocking `typeof(T?)` with `T : class` also applies here. `typeof(T?)` means precisely the same thing as `typeof(T)` for any possible `T`, class or struct. ([SharpLab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:CYLg1APgAgTABAYQLACgDeq5blALHAWQEYAeAFQD4AKASk2wxW2bgDcBDAJznbgF44AFwCeABwCmAewBmVMjQDc9Fmy5wARvyFipssgH5FyuAF9UJoA=)) This fact only changes if you add a struct constraint.

In addition, the same warning message would still make sense here. `T?` inside a method without a `struct` constraint is a "defaultable T" nullable reference types annotation.

